Take-Home Assignment

Integrations Education Transformation - Nick Lieurance

Priorities during my first 90 days

We already know integrations education content is inconsistent. But we don't yet have a complete picture of what needs improvement. I'd spend my first 90 days exploring the people, processes, and resources behind this problem. Then I'd build on those efforts with my first long-term initiative.

1. Understand how integrations education works today.

What Id do

  • Meet with Education, Engineering, Product, and Support partners.
  • Shadow an integration release to observe real workflows.
  • Document where information moves and where it stalls.

Why it matters
Content fails when ownership is unclear. Understanding how work happens today gives us the clarity we need to improve accuracy, consistency, and velocity.

How Id measure impact

  • Documented workflow with owners + handoff
  • Identified friction points ranked by severity
  • Alignment from partners who validate the map

2. Audit integrations content against user needs.

What Id do

  • Evaluate Help Center + Academy content for accuracy, duplication, and structure.
  • Review top integration-related support tickets. #quick-win
  • Prioritize fixes by user impact and support volume. #quick-win

Why it matters
Users rely on integrations documentation to self-serve. When content is confusing or inconsistent, Support absorbs the cost.

How Id measure impact

  • Audit completed with recommendations
  • List of updates ranked by user impact
  • Early improvements shipped

3. Build lightweight systems that make content consistent.

What Id do

  • Create templates for setup and troubleshooting guides.
  • Build an integrations glossary for shared language. #quick-win
  • Draft publishing guidance to standardize content. #quick-win

Why it matters
Standards reduce rework, improve clarity, and make future content easier to maintain, especially as integrations scale.

How Id measure impact

  • Templates and glossary in use
  • Reduction in duplicate or conflicting content
  • Faster content creation from cross-functional teams

Measuring & communicating ROI

How Id measure integrations education

Focus on whether content helps users self-serve, adopt integrations faster, and depend less on Support.

Metric What it tells us
Integration-related ticket volume Are users unblocked without Support?
AI/self-service deflection Is content answering questions early?
Time-to-resolution When users need help, can Support solve faster?
Article usefulness + search success Can users find and apply guidance?
Activation + setup completion Are integrations easier to configure end-to-end?

How Id track and report progress

  • Set baselines in the first 90 days.
  • Track changes monthly to show movement over time.
  • Surface trends and patterns, not just numbers.

How Id communicate business value to leadership

Id report results using a lightweight dashboard and narrative updates like:

"Integration-related tickets dropped 14% quarter-over-quarter after we made documentation improvements. This reduced troubleshooting and freed Support for higher-complexity issues."

Long-term initiative

Problem

Integrations content lives across multiple channels and follows different creation processes. This leads to duplication, uneven depth, and content thats hard to discover. As a result, we see slower setup and troubleshooting for users and internal teams.

Audience

  • Users setting up or managing integrations
  • Design, Education, Engineering, Product, and Support teams
  • Anyone who creates, updates, or relies on integrations content

Desired outcomes

  • One consistent system for how integrations content is created and maintained
  • Less duplication and faster updates
  • Clearer paths to answers for customers
  • Better activation and reduced ticket volume

Process

1. Explore the problem space.

What Id do:

  • Interview contributors across Design, Education, Engineering, Product, and Support.
  • Observe real integration releases and content creation workflows.
  • Audit tools, documentation sources, and handoff points.

Output: A current-state workflow map showing ownership, gaps, and friction points.

2. Translate findings into insights.

What Id do:

  • Build lightweight personas for internal contributors and end users.
  • Map journeys for content creation and content consumption.
  • Identify the top breakdowns by frequency and impact.

Output: A summary of pain points and opportunities, prioritized by user impact.

3. Brainstorm solutions.

What Id do:

  • Co-create ideas with partners during a short workshop or async review.
  • Explore options for improving communication, ownership, and content quality.
  • Define what good looks like for integrations education.

Output: A shortlist of solutions with effort estimates and expected outcomes.

4. Prototype one solution.

What Id do:

  • Select one idea with the highest impact-to-effort ratio.
  • Build a working version (templates, a workflow, guidelines, a structure model).
  • Run it with a small set of integrations content.

Output: A functional pilot that partners can use and react to in real workflows.

5. Test and iterate.

What Id do:

  • Collect feedback from Product, Support, and internal contributors.
  • Track early signals like reduced rework or faster updates.
  • Improve based on what we learn.

Output: A refined, scalable solution ready for broader rollout.
